reviews:
Had to get my bank involved due to their trickery with my deposit.

This review is to warn that my deposit was not returned within the two week time frame. I gave them a few extra days to do the right thing too but instead they lied and said my bank rejected the reimbursement of funds. This never happens.

Please note that if a hotel tells you it's taking money out of your account as deposit, thats a major problem. Hotels don't need to have the money leave the account to have a deposit on you staying.

Also the room view was naff and the breakfast looked average. Nothing that special even without the scamming

We were happy to stay in a less touristy part of the city and this area can certainly be described as urban gritty. It is easy to walk to either Belleville or Pyrenees for the metro - line 11 - and if you take it to the end and get off at Chatelet, there are loads of connection options
The room was big (by Paris standards) - we booked a superior room to get a bit more space. It was very clean and bright with 2 large windows fronted by juliet balconies - it was nice to open the windows and let in some fresh air and we were on the 4th floor so the noise level was ok. The bathroom is small, but the shower was excellent - a big walk in space with loads of pressure and piping hot water at all times
Staff are friendly although we didn't have much interaction with them to be fair. We had breakfast one day - which is a decent enough spread - but at 14 euros a head probably not worth it - you can get better deals at local cafes. There are lots of bars and eateries nearby to choose from
If we had a couple of gripes, it would be that there was no hand towel - just a big towel each, and it would have been nice to have a mirror in the bedroom - the only one was in the bathroom, but these are small things.

We had a fantastic stay at this hotel near Belleville metro station.

Our flight was delayed which made our late arrival even later. The hotel called to confirm our travel plans and reassured us that checking in wouldn’t be an issue.

Our room was clean and well kept with a safe. The bathroom had a fantastic power shower, which we enjoyed after long days of walking.

Hotel staff were friendly and we would generally recommend that others choose this accommodation when in Paris.

Very stylish hotel in the heart of Belleville. Surrounded by great restaurants, with a two large parks nearby. I stayed with my wife, baby, and dog. We felt very welcomed. Most of the staff we encountered spoke good English, which is a huge plus for me!

This hotel is in a great location in the heart of bustling Belleville with good connections on the metro (Lignes 2 and 11 from Belleville) to the rest of central Paris. Reception is efficient and helpful, the rooms clean and comfortable with, yes, the best shower we have ever experienced in a hotel. We appreciated the lift to our fourth floor room. Do check out the lovely nearby parks when you have had enough of noise, hustle and bustle although the Rue du Jouye-Rouve is very quiet. We did not try the breakfast but had a very decent one at Saraccin in the Rue de Tourtille @ 6euros.

We were really looking forward to our trip here (booked pre-covid) but then our flights were cancelled 3 months ago due to the pandemic. We contacted the hotel straight away but were told we had booked a non-cancellable and non-transferable room so they were not willing to let us cancel the room.
We repeatedly messaged them as various quarantine rules became in force but always with the same result.
I then messaged a final time this week due to the Paris curfew (ie e writhing closing at 9pm) to be told “Dear Mr. Smith,
You have made a non-modifiable and non-cancellable reservation.
The Scarlett hotel is still open. The curfew is from 9pm to 6am and every body must adapt to this exceptional situation.
We are sorry to announce you that we can not refund or defer the booking.
Best regards,
The management”
Several other hotels that I and my friends have booked have worked with us to try and compromise (eg take a deposit, defer through booking to 2021 etc) so I am extremely disappointed in the hotel’s attitude. “Non-cancellabe and non-refundable” do not really apply to the conditions we are all living in during 2020 so to have them thrown back in my face by a robotic reservations clerk is frustrating and insulting.

The location is just fantastic, as you are right in the heart of cool Belleville, with all its great restaurants and bars. The decor and style of the hotel is modern bohemian and fits perfectly in the neighbourhood. Rooms are small, but have all you need. And who is actually spending much time in the hotel room when visiting Paris? We will defintely stay her again on our next trip to Paris.

Tres chic hotel, lovely room, even USB plugs, fabulous bathroom with the best shower in a hotel we have ever experienced. Great location for easy parking and yet close to central Paris, and a lovely view of the Eiffel Tower on the short walk from the Metro.
Friendly and welcoming staff. You won't find better in Paris.

Really nice room, clean and well decorated / furnished. Great shower. Nice bathroom (small). Room a bit small, but had a large window that had a view on a sunny quiet courtyard. Really enjoyed my stay and will stay again. Great sleep! Breakfast was a nice touch. Hotel right next door to organic store and nice book store. Also close to a park that has a great view on the city.

Very well situated away from the tourist center, staying in this hotel gives the feel to really be in Paris. Night live around: plenty of students, multiculti with Asiatic touch. Well connected with metro and bus. The hotel is very clean and neat. The suit we lived in has no daylight. So you need to be on tour in Paris and come for sleeping only. Super friendly service.

Beautiful hotel, small & cosy. Comfy mattress and spotless bathrooms. Staff are friendly and location is close to metro and a park, plenty of restaurants and bars around. Read a previous review it is not "ghetto" it's Paris and its beautiful!

The hotel was well placed re: metro, bars and restaurants. It was quiet, clean, trendy, comfortable. The staff were friendly and helpful. We would stay again. Oh and note the Lebanese restaurant up the road is amazing!

Smelly hotel in a ghetto, no elevator to some floors (only a spiral staircase) very uncomfortable to go up and down with luggage. Naim was very helpful. Do no stay hear it is very very very far from everything and in a really unsafe neighborhood. Do not stay here, it's 30 minutes from the sites by taxi

A really beautiful little gem. My room was impeccable, clean + quiet + comfortable + beautifully decorated. Staff was extremely friendly, no problems with after-hours access or slightly late check-out. Not a big touristy thing, this is a tiny "boutique hotel" in a renovated old house.
The location could be a slight minus or a big plus. It's in a side street next to all the Chinese/ Asian restaurants in Belleville. Great Asian food (dumplings noodles etc!) right around the corner! (also kebabs, Thai, african..) It was NOT noisy but it's not exactly the typical Parisian "croissants and croque-monsieur on the Champs Élysée" either. It's multiculti. For the younger and the adventurous.. yes!

Went to Paris for a week and had a good experience here. The hotel is located walking distance to the Metro Station. Also You will be able to find nice bars & restaurants around it. Staff friendly. Bed so comfortable, room is nice and quiet. Wi Fi works fast and is reliable. For being Paris prices are more than ok. The buffet breakfast it is ok.

Hello
Staying at the hotel scarlet this month for a special trip with my fiancée any recommendations on places to eat? and any advice on where to park please?
Does the hotel include breakfast with the price we paid or is it cheaper to stop at a cafe each morning we're only there for 3 nights and doing Disney land 1 day.

We are driving from England. Many thanks

This is a nice hotel in an area of Paris that is not full of tourists.
The good parts are that you can go and get a drink, a sandwich and a meal without feeling violated! Also it’s ideally located for the Pyrenees metro stop. The hotel rooms are nice, fairly small but perfectly adequate. There are no coffee making facilities in the room but you can get one from the small dining room at a cost of €3.50.
There is a McDonalds about 150 metres up the hill if you want.
There is a stunning bakery nearby where we got breakfast, chose not to eat in the hotel as they wanted €13, I’m from Yorkshire so have short arms and deep pockets!!
The area is not very picturesque and walked from Gard North train station which wasn’t a very pleasant walk!
I must mention the staff who were very helpful and friendly.
Summing up, would I stay here again? Absolutely.

Stayed with partner for her birthday, lovely and modern hotel, very clean and nice staff. Bed was so comfy and really quiet slept lovely!!
Bit random but the smell in the lobby was amazing would love to know what sort of infusers they use!

Beautiful design hotel, in an interesting area which shows a different , more real / original side of Paris away from the touristy parts. There are a few little issues with the hotel but the design and comfort as well as price more than compensate for the small issues. At first I was apprehensive about the area but after exploring a bit, I fell in Love with it...this is one part of Paris where people are so real and genuine but its not everyone’s cup of tea if you cannot deal with working class neighbourhoods then stay elesewhere....however if you are open minded and artistic then this is an amazing unspoilt part of Paris that you can fall in love with.

The hotel itself has stunning design, the rooms are comfortable and spacious by Paris standards and for the price its a good deal overall.

Most or the staff members at this hotel were very Kind and helpful and sweet, however one lady was very rude to me and her bad behaviour really put me down, I already complained about it to her and let her know there is no reason to be rude to me, over a very small issue which was not even my fault as I had explained to her calmly but she was just not interested in being nice and kept talking to me in an insulting demeaning manner that made me feel very bad and insulted. I was very angry at first and wanted to raise a huge complaint but then I thought about it and felt that Paris is a stressful difficult city where a lot of people are struggling, so they turn a bit rude and give this beautiful city a bad reputation , we need to look past it and forgive them for their rudeness and enjoy the good things this amazing city has to offer. I actually feel sorry for her now , maybe if the owners of the hotel looked after their staff properly and kept them happy as well as trained them well enough to deal with guests then this would not happen. Anyway if I didn’t have this bad experience i would have given this hotel 4 / 5...as it is quite a nice little gem in Paris.

P.s....don’t be put off by the area...there’s a beautiful park at the end of the street where this hotel is, and some amazing cheap restaurants all around....give the area a chance and you would be pleasantly surprised.

Not at all what I was expecting. Room was nice and location was great for me. Right in the middle of loads of a diverse neighbourhood full of life and cafes etc. The amazing Belleville Park is right next door HOWEVER what exactly is this hotel?! It might serve drinks but it does not actually have a bar. If it does I missed it. Also the terrace seems to be a few metres of pavement in the middle of the building.
There seems to be a wiring issue in my room as the lights suddenly turn on whenever they feel like it. Also someone forgot the soundproofing. I can hear everything in the hallway and also the street.

the rooms are not isolated acoustically!
Rooms where you will feel like take shower/dry hair/go to the toilet with the people next door, the carpet was wet from a leaky shower, the service minimum and arrogant, really disappointing!

This was our second stay at Hotel Scarlet and it was delightful. The rooms are rather small, but that is to be expected in Paris. Everything was very clean and well appointed. Staff were very helpful. The hotel is away from the main tourist sites but not too far. The Ile de la cite and other places are easily accessible from the nearby metro stations.
We went to Lao Siam for a great Thai experience and to a wonderful Lebanese restaurant, L' Artisan Libanais, within a short walking distance on the main road from the hotel as recommended by staff.

Overall a great experience!

The hotel is beautiful. Rooms are cozy and well appointed. The staff is very friendly. The only issue I have is the lack of clarity in the location. It is in an up-and-coming gentrifying neighborhood, quite a distance from the main Paris attractions. Example, it’s a 45 minute walk to Le Marais.
The staff was friendly and helpful. In terms of value, I found a better hotel with the Superior location at 20% less.

found a gem!
this great new hotel has it all...
loevly welcome and comfy clean cosy room
amazing new part of town for me
coolest little cafe down the road
baratin restaurant next door is next level
staff are amazing getting me a table on busy friday night
brilliant recomendations of a cool bar in the park up the road
cant wait to go back
thanks for a mega weekend

We visited hotel scarlett last year for a long weekend whilst celebrating a birthday. The staff were very friendly and welcoming. Our room was spotless, fresh and modern and yes they're not the biggest but we weren't visiting Paris to admire the views from the room so we weren't in the room very long. The bed was comfy and the shower was good which was all that matters to us. The location isn't in the nicest of areas but it suited us being close to the metro and being fairly central. We would definitely stay here again if visiting Paris again.

The room was a lovely standard, although on the petit size it was roomy enough for a city break and made the most of the space available. The shower was amazing and the bed was very comfy. The location of the hotel is fantastic, 3 stops from Gard du nord underground and pretty much within 30mins to all major attractions. There is a beautiful park around the corner called Belleview park which was lovely for picnics and view of the city. Many lovely eateries just a few minutes walk from the hotel. I would definitely recommend and would stay there again if we are back in Paris.

This small hotel is in the belleville district of Paris. Its a two train metro ride away from gare de nord. Perfectly located for us. we stayed room only. No tea/coffee making facilities in room. However rooms were perfect. A comfy bed, clean and warm. Reception staff were friendly and helpful. within walking diastance is a metro and some locals shops and bakeries. As a base for Paris this ideal and would recommend.

Thank you to everyone at this wonderful hotel for making me so welcome. This hotel is a breath of fresh air having a relaxed and open feel, very helpful staff, well appointed is perhaps compact (like most of Paris) rooms.

The area is a bit colourful, but the hotel is near the Metro and there are some very nice artisan small bakers and food shops. For a taste of everyday life in a non tourist area and a great stay, this is the place. I personally found this colourful mix refreshing and enjoyable when contrasted to "tourist" Paris,

If you’re looking for a clean and simple hotel, then this is it. It’s overpriced if you have to pay the regular price, but if you happen to get a bargain, it’s great. It can get really loud if guests are leaving in the morning.

I was taken away to Paris for a birthday celebration with my husband.

I booked this hotel, as it was fairly close to our main event of the weekend & it looked good on the internet via Expedia.

Pleasent reception when arrived.
Shown to the lift after the initial booking in process & clear instructions as to our room location.

The room was although compact, very well presented & clean.
Double bed- crisp clean sheets
Shower room- perfectly formed.
Toilet -was with a powerful flush & adequate toilet roll provided
Great powerful shower -which you could vary the temperature
Lovely big bath towels- which can be a miss in some hotels.
Breakfast- (only viewed, not sampled) was a bit of a predictable affair (cereal, toast, tea, coffee)

My one criticism, was the hotel room was roasting.
Even on reporting that the temperature control panel was faulty, at least twice to reception staff throughout our weekend stay, it was not fixed & we were not furnished with any explanation as to why it remained faulty.
This made for a very uncomfortable nights sleep, which didn’t contribute to a restful weekend.
Especially as to counter balance to this -our only solution was to open the sound proof windows to the noisey street outside. Shame.

Our room was ground floor of a little courtyard it was clean comfortable and big enough for the 4 of us,the staff were friendly and it was between 2 metro stations.wevisited a couple of local bars which was fun and had dinner in the restaurant next door Le baratin which wasn’t really our cup of tea

The staff at the hotel were great, my reservation kept cancelling when booking through third party websites, and Sonia rang me when she realised and explained what was happening, and rebooked the room for us - A Superior Double room.

We arrived to the hotel just after midday - the hotel is located close to two metro stops, Belleville and Pyrenees. As we walked in the decor in the lobby area took our attention, it’s designed beautifully.

Sonia was on reception, she was welcoming and check in was swift. Luckily for us our room was ready - room 103.

We then took the lift to our floor, now the lift had us in absolute hysterics. You really should get the Guinness World Record Books around and see if it qualifies as the worlds smallest lift - we had no issue with it, it added a comedic factor for us.

Rooms are in the average to small side, but again the chic decor continued throughout the hotel. The room compromised of a regular double bed, a desk with chair, a mini bar, wardrobe and of course the bathroom - shower only.

We are not sure what we paid for extra with being in the superior double room as the mini bar items came at an extra cost and there was nothing else that stood out for us.

Location of this hotel is excellent with many restaurants and shops nearby, and just a short distance from Paris Gare Du Nord station via Metro.

We would definitely stay here again, but wouldn’t pay the extra price for a superior room.

Thanks for everything!

I received a notification after my initial reservation that my booking was not confirmed after all, so I decided to give this hotel a quick call to double check...

The lady on the phone was incredible unfriendly and impolite answering in a very unprofessional manner. So I decided with so many hotels around to go elsewhere. Too bad though, the pictures look amazing but I believe that the first impression should be right.

Things you need to know:
Very small hotel with small rooms. Very small lift to fit 1 person with 1 bag. Very friendly staff. You are almost half way between 2 subway stations. The walk from the stations is down a hill, so when we were going to hotel we went to station up hill and walked down. When we were leaving hotel walked down hill to other station.
We did not find much near the hotel in the way of shops or dinning, so be prepared to use train to commute. We did not have control of the room temperature so we had to open the window to let in cool air. Very loud Street noise most all night.
I really feel like a 3.5 rating would be more accurate, but 3 is to low. Would I stay here again? Probably not. Do I regret staying here? Not at all.

Perfect and best service. Very sympathic people at the reception. Room very clean, bathroom nice and clean, bed comfortable. Nice surrounding. Nice and interesting quartier. Breakfast very good. All what you need. Good Price.

My daughter and myself had a great time in Paris and this cute hotel is part of it!
We arrived earlier than the check-in time and we’re put in a room immediately. Nice and cozy well decorated room with a comfortable bed, hot shower, a safe for your belongings in case it’s needed. It’s small but I believe this is how rooms are in Paris hotels. Very affordable price.
Breakfast was delicious! Staff was very helpful and they all spoke English which was a big help for us.
The location is great! It’s situated in a neighborhood where you see lots of locals buying their baguettes before going home at the end of the day. Yeah, some nice Boulangeries are just a few steps away besides the Carrefour market. Also, metro is very close too.
I’d go back to it without any hesitation...Lovely place!

You have to carry the luggage’s to first floor on your own (which is difficult carrying heavy). The elevator is so small and located at a very difficult space. Room and bathroom is okay. Location is good, with close by metro. But the hotel charged us 90 euros extra as a deposit that will be released on checkout, which we still haven’t received.
The staffs are nice but lack of communication between them, we had to ask 3 different staffs to book a taxi to airport.

The fairy tale at the website of the Scarlett hotel in Paris is incomplete and incorrect. Take the ‘Superior Twin’ (we stayed in room 801) it may be large enough for Sleepy Dwarf and his mate, however not for two grown-ups. The beds are just 1.80 m long, equipped with a single mattress and a 100% synthetic (sweaty) duvet. The bathroom is only as wide as twice the lavatory bowl. And there is no elevator for the rooms at the back of the hotel. These are solely accessible through a rather narrow steepish staircase (likewise fire escape!)
Like canned sardines guests can have a convenience self-service breakfast in the tiny room behind the reception. All ingredients are efficiently packed as single portions in disposable (plastic) packaging. You’ll be better off at the real bakery just around the corner.
We love fairy tales, not lying stories, accompanied by false evocative, dressed up wide-angle shots.

For decades we visit Paris several times a year and stayed in quite a few hotels. We know by now what level of facilities you may expect for your money. For the Scarlett we have paid € 192.00 for one night, including breakfast, far too much for the poor standard of this accommodation.

The hotel was situated in what we'd call 'true Paris'. Coming from the tourist area that day into the streets where the hotel was situated we could see this is where the 'real' people live and it was a good experience to see both sides of Paris. We couldn't fault the hotel or its staff. The rooms were just like it was depicted in the photographs and I had a better nights sleep there than I had expected for a city hotel. The bed was very comfortable and hotel had a pleasant ambiance. We really enjoyed breakfast, there was plenty of choice and it set us up for the busy day ahead that we had planned.
Overall, it was a welcomed sanctuary for us from the hustle and bustle of grand Paris.

I've been to Paris many times and tend to stay in the Belleville area because I love the local flavour (and Tunisian and Asian restaurants that don't break the bank!). This was my first time staying at this hotel, though, and it was great. The rooms are the standard small size for Paris (it's worth upgrading to a "superior"), but they have just been renovated and everything is new. Some rooms over look the street (it's around the corner from the main street but it was still fairly noisy) and some have windows that just face the room a few metres away. So I think it depends on the room you get. The breakfast was good, with some eggs, meats, and all the usual pastries. We didn't find a good breakfast spot in the neighbourhood that wasn't just a pastry and coffee, so we stayed here for breakfast each morning. The staff are really great: friendly, helpful and really wanted to please guests. We really appreciated them!

First time in this hotel in the area called Belleville what a nice pleasant surprise we will definitely return, a bustling area but the hotel itself is in a nice quiet street, not far from the metro and only 15 min max from the heart of Paris, its perfect

We would not recommend this Hotel and we would recommend if you are staying demand not to stay in room 702. We complained during our stay about the room as it had not external window, was not as advertised, smelt of Marijuana or damp, had intermittently working air condition and was smaller than advertised. On complaining to the staff there we were told they had previously received complaints about the room but couldn't move us as they were fully booked. We were not offered compensation even though the Hotel admitted the room was not as advertised!!!

Further to this our toiletries were not changed and the mini bar was not restocked during our 2 night stay.

Shocking hotel,having stayed in Paris a number of times I would avoid this Hotel and recommend AirBnB when travelling to Paris.

First thing that needs addressing is given that this hotel is in Paris you have to accept the rooms are on the small side that being said for the two of us the space never really became an issue as we only had one bag etc.

The area that hotel scarlett is a tad "urban" but that being said neither of us felt unsafe returning to the hotel late at night.

The location is a distance out from the main sites of Paris for example the hotel to the eiffel tower is 37mins using public transport or 1hour 40mins on foot so even though the hotel is reasonable you also have to factor in the cost of constant metro journeys or the time you will spend walking to where ever you want to be.

The only issues we had with the room is the lack of air conditioning, it has air conditioning but when i mentioned it not working the staff said its currently on heat rather than cool as they thought it wasn't warm well it certainly was warm which leads on to the next issue our room overlooked the road therefore it was seldom quiet and trying to sleep with the windows open was impossible.

I'm not sure if I would return to the Hotel Scarlett due to the distance from the main sites that being said you cant ignore the massive price difference between this hotel and the hotels close to the sites.

Room was great - Very modern, big sized TV, spotlessly clean and a fantastic shower. the room is very modern and pretty big in comparison to other options in Paris.
Breakfast is pretty basic but gives you all the needed energy to start the day.
Front desk staff were very helpful with solutions to problems that rose.
The only problem because of which I didn't give this hotel a 5 star review is the location. Although not very far from the center of Paris - Only 4-5 metro stops to central paris - and a good proximity to Pyrenees (3 min walk) and to Belville (5 min walk) stations - the neighborhood is a little shabby. Lots of immigrants, strange shops. It's not that you don't feel safe, but it is not the classical Paris surrounding you would expect from a Parisian hotel. Another drawback is that the hotel is close to the top of the hill, which means that traveling with the Metro - you have to climb up or down when you are arriving. What we did is to go in the morning downhill to Bellville station and coming back in the evening - stopping at Pyrenees station and downhill again.
Overall - I reccomend the stay at the Scarlett, with a very good value for money.

A real gem in an non-touristic area of Paris. This little hotel has been fully renovated and it is just perfect. The room was small but spacious enough. The breakfast was simple but made of fresh ingredients. The service was totally lovely. At that price, this is outstanding value!

This hotel is wonderful. Cozy, well designed, clean, confortable, greatly located. The staff is just friendly and really helpful. The rooms are confortable, small but extremely well designed. The cleaness is perfect.
Location wise it is a perfect spot. Belleville is a fun part of Paris with lovely little restaurants, bars, funky spots. I strongly recommand!There is a safe in the room.

Great small hotel. Perfect neighbourhood if you want to get away from the most turist filled parts of Paris. Kind of a ruff neighbourhood with it's own charm. Friendly and welcoming staff. Great AC in the room.

The rooms at the Scarlett hotel gives you a very comfortable feeling. After walking around all day it's very nice to come back home to clean and neat room. The bathrooms were spotless and bright. The employees were very nice and helpful. Your very close to metro stations and a very lively neighborhood with many food options. Sonia at the front desk was very informative, with places to eat and stay away from, good suggestion to were to go around Paris and explore the neighborhood. Thank you everyone at the Scarlett

Hotel Scarlett was the type of place that you can tell was designed and is maintained with a lot of love. The employees are friendly and helpful and the design is beautiful and very modern. The facilities all functioned great and are comfortable. The room we stayed in had plenty of room for our luggage and a desk space and other flat surfaces to place things.

The wireless internet was easily accessed and worked great for looking up things, but was slow to upload picture on a text or a post and sometimes didn’t work. It forced me to be more present and not waste time posting or texting photos to family. That being said, it worked great for texting without pictures or watching videos.

One of the things I loved about this hotel was the location. It is placed in an area that has a strong community and is away from the main tourist attractions, yet is easy access to everything with the Metro being so close. There are great restaurants, bakeries, and bars all around this area and lots of diversity. I also love all of the street art in this neighborhood.

One night walking back to the hotel, after eating at a vegetarian restaurant in the neighborhood, we passed by a bar that had what seemed to be an impromptu band playing in the alley out front. We listened to this great band play, while people danced sang along, and celebrated the music and beauty of the evening. At the same time and place, a street artist created this incredible mural on the side of the building using spray paint. The experience was great fun and gave us a real feel for the locals in Paris. What an unexpected treat!

If you’re questioning whether or not you’d like to stay in Belleville, I can say this unique and creative part of Paris is worth visiting, and Hotel Scarlett is a wonderful sanctuary at the end of a busy touring day.

Great experience! The hotel is located between two metro stations And also a direct bus connnection (26) from Gare du Nord. Room was not big but efficiënt. Only missed a place to put my suitcase on. WiFi could be better. In 2 minutes you have at the Parc de Belleville a very nice view over the city. I didn’t’ do the breakfast cause many bakeries close to the hotel and also a carrefour city. Definetely would recommend this hotel.

This hotel is an perfect little sanctuary in the heart of vibrant Belleville. The location is ideal. The neighborhood is alive and diverse, the food options plentiful and fabulous from cheese plates and wine to the best dumplings I have ever tasted. It is a lived in neighborhood now inhabited by a young energetic crowd. The park is lovely. 2 metro stops are steps away but roaming out of Belleville by foot gets you to other wonderful neighborhoods. The hotel itself is clean and cool and the bed and shower were fabulous, great staff. Still affordable. Will be back soon!

Service and accommodations were above expectation. Clean air conditioned rooms with friendly staff! Really enjoyed short conversation with Sonia. Easy check in and convenient metro accessible location. Nice view of Eiffel Tower. Neighborhood is a bit grungy but more than safe. My husband and I frequently walked the neighborhood after 1AM which was still lively. Overall pleasant stay!

This hotel was a great value and a fantastic experience in a wonderful little corner of Paris.

The rooms were stylish, modern, and luxurious. Our room had everything we needed despite being quite compact. Front desk service was outstanding and they even brought ice up to the room upon my request.

The hotel is right between Parc des Buttes-Chaumont and Parc de Belleville, both of which are beautiful. It was very convenient to both bus and metro lines, and had great restaurants nearby. It’s in a non-touristy part of Paris, which makes it feel so much more real.

I saw a review that complained about there not being an elevator and wanted to respond. There are two wings of the hotel. One has four floors and has an elevator, and the other wing without an elevator only has two floors. Most people would be able to carry their bags up one flight of stairs, but it’s true this would not be an accessible hotel to those using a wheelchair.

We thoroughly enjoyed our stay and would return!

This was a return visit to the Hotel Scarlett. We stayed here in 2017 for 4 days and returned this year for a week. We love the industrial chic design in the common areas and our room was spacious enough and the shower was great! The hotel staff is very helpful and breakfast is available for an up charge if desired. While we did not get the breakfast, it looked lovely. We love the Belleville neighborhood- the metros are very close- either Belleville or Pyrenees. We will absolutely return to this hotel.

I absolutely hated hotel scarlett, but I really blame myself for trying to save a few bucks.
Given that it is summer and high season and the room was way less than $150 euro a night, what was I expecting?

First, the good. I love, love, love the 20th. it is rough and raw and edgy and full of crazy characters and artists' ateliers--so different from the manicured blandness of the 6th. Hotel Scarlett is literally next door to my favorite restaurant in Paris and spitting distance from le grand Bain, another on my top ten list. there is also an amazing wine store/bar right across the street that has an huge selection of unusual and well priced bottles and hosts quite a party scene every night. our shower was powerful and hot. the towels were huge and thirsty. and the bed was quite comfortable. (I loved the custom woven hotel scarlett design, but I did have to question why they used so much of their design budget on that when we were given a tiny sliver of soap for a five day stay and it was not replaced even when it melted into nothing -- we literally had to go to the front desk to beg for more.)

Sadly, the list of what I didn't like is far longer. first, there is no elevator. and though the check in vaguely offers to help you with your bags, I really didn't believe the clerk had any interest in carrying my giant suitcase up the curvy and difficult staircase. the wallpaper in the hallway is tatty, ripped and stained in multiple places. in the morning, hotel staff leave cleaning equipment and bags of linens at the foot of the stairs, not only in clear sight of guests, but I literally had to climb over them to get out of the hotel. our bathroom door was scuffed and filthy, the ceiling in the shower had huge sections with peeling paint (yuck) and every towel I used had makeup stains on it. the led light next to my bed flickered on and off our whole stay making me wonder if anyone checks the rooms ever. don't forget the soap. the teensy tiny piece of soap they gave us to last five days for two people. and then there was the noise. this place is noisy. the walls are so thin you can hear everything that happens in the hallway and in other rooms. worse, our room had a window to an enclosed courtyard so everything echoed making a little rainstorm sound like the end of the world and a family eating breakfast like a school full of children after too much birthday cake. but the worst was the air conditioning. we'd get the room nice and cool before bed (it was hot and humid during our stay) and in the middle of the night, it would just go off. my husband would get up and tinker with it and it would get cool again, and then a few hours later it would go off again. at first, I thought maybe we'd just reached the set temperature, but when I found myself literally dripping in sweat under the covers, I realized either it was broken or the system was rigged to turn off no matter the room's temperature.

I was hoping for a sweet little design hotel, well priced because it is in one of the least expensive neighborhoods in Paris, something like mama shelter, but I found hotel Scarlett to be more like a hostel in quality and service level. I thought the cleanliness was iffy. and when at checkout, the clerk actually counted my total owed on her fingers, I realized the staff was, well, a little green, which explained a lot.

Hotel Scarlett is conveniently located close to restaurants/bars/boulangeries which I love. It's also close to the train station so you can easily go to different tourist spots in Paris. Hotel itself is vlean and staff is very pleasant and accommodating.

Boutique style hotel, nicely decorated.
We stayed in the suite on the ground floor which was a good size and beautifully finished.
The staff were helpful and we liked the area (not touristy at all), with plenty of restaurants, the metro stop is around the corner from the hôtel and its 10/15 mins to the hôtel de ville area.

Small super-friendly sparkly-clean stylish hotel , opened only a couple of years ago in the Belleville area of Paris. Rooms are small but so comfortable, buffet breakfast good value at 14euros and the area is vibrant, ethnically diverse and very welcoming with a huge range of shops cafes and restaurants nearby. Loved it!

We only spent one night at Hotel Scarlett on our way through Paris but are so glad we got off the beaten path and found this little gem hidden in the Belleville neighborhood. The hotel rooms were on the smallish side but that was to be expected. The decor was eclectic and charming. The staff were absolutely wonderful - kind, helpful, generous of their time and attention. I know we will be back someday!

My girlfriend and I spent three nights here in March, and had a wonderful stay. I arrived 4 hours before the check in time, just off the red-eye and was pleasantly surprised when they were able to check me in and give me a room with no prior notice. The room was just as advertised, with a few minor issues. Some of the lights didn't work, and the bathroom door didn't latch. But the biggest issue was that we could hear nearly everything in the small staircase just outside. We were lucky to have quiet other guests around us, but I can imagine that being a larger issue with different people staying nearby.

All of the staff were very professional and very friendly, especially given that I speak very little French. It is located in a charming neighborhood with a nice grocery store next door and a short walk from the Pyrénées metro station. The bread shop right next to the metro entrance and the metro cafe nextdoor were also wonderful.

I'd highly recommend Hotel Scarlett to anyone looking for a less-touristy place to stay in Paris, and am incredibly grateful to the staff there for making our trip wonderful!

Hotel Scarlett is a new place in Paris in the nice Bellville district. Rooms are small but well equipped and convenient. The shower is great! The staff is very friendly. Our room was on the street side. Unfortunately there was some noise during the night. One topic could be better. We ordered a bottle of wine form the reception. The wine was nice but € 32 ......

Overall, we generally liked this hotel and LOVED the neighbourhood.

Good:
Stylish
Cute
Mature/adult clientele
Friendly staff
Great hipstery non touristy neighbourhood
Strong wifi

Not so good:
Noise - could hear every door open and close throughout the night & cleaning staff started up at 8am on Sunday morning
Shower sprayed all over tiny bathroom
No ventilation in the room - smelled like weed and/or feet

I complained about the noise and the front desk offered us a free pastry and coffee.

Would probably return, but would bring earplugs!!

Stayed here for four nights and had a great experience. The hotel was very nice and quaint. Hotel room size was decent, especially for Paris. The rooms were well appointed and clean. Reasonably priced hotel well located near restaurants and public transit for exploring the city.

I really loved this hotel and had the most wonderful time in Paris. The local food was accessible and the neighborhood was fun and ethnic. This hotel had a delicious breakfast plus it was walking distance from Parc des Buttes-Chaumont (must not miss) and Parc De Belleville. The staff was very accommodating and down the hill you could see the top of the Eiffel Tower. The "subways" were 7 min walking distance. I really cant complaint about this romantic little hotel. I didn't even care that the rooms were snug.

Stayed here with my partner for 3 nights. Loved it! The room was huge as was the bathroom, the bed very comfortable and the view was amazing. We stayed on the top level and the windows opens out and looked out over the cobble road. At night the restaurant on the road below had an accordion playing so we lay on bed listening to it and had a very French experience. The staff were very helpful and could speak English which helped. A bit of a trek to to city but the staff were very helpful with instructions and directions. Would defiantly recommend and would stay again.

Was comfortable as soon as we walked through the door great decor really friendly staff everything Explained well in English.
The room wasn’t huge but hey it’s Paris however it’s really nicely decorated and the bed was mega comfortable. Very clean and warm.
Bathroom odd shape but again modern and functional good water pressure great shower.
A safe was available for free and a minibar which was not free lol
Breakfast was typical of France, cereal bread hams and salamis fruit tea coffee and fruit juices not sure it’s worth €14 but was plentiful and fresh.
Also given 5% discount for next visit. I emailed them about the pillows they use which are mega and they emailed me back same day with a link as to where to get them! what more could you ever ask for?

This was our second stay at the Scarlett this year and again it didn't disappoint. The hotel is new, modern and super clean, with an amazing breakfast selection in the morning. The staff is lovely as well, really professional and helpful.
Definitely recommending!

Situated in a Parisian area of Paris it would help to know a little basic French.
From CDG Airport take the RAT Train to Chalet, then take the Brown Metro line to Pyrenees, when leaving the Metro head down the Left hand side of McDonald's and it's the 2nd street on your left down the hill....Look and you'll catch a glimpse of the Eiffel Tower😁 One ticket €10.20 Will cover Train & Metro.
Hotel staff speak enough English to help you with anything you need.

My room at Hotel Scarlett was absolutely gorgeous. The room decor is modern and sophisticated yet still very homey. The bed was also extremely comfortable! Both the bedroom and the bathroom were spotlessly clean. The breakfast options are simple but delicious. Lastly, the staff at the hotel is fantastic- welcoming, helpful and efficient.
I would definitely recommend the hotel to anyone visiting Paris if they're looking for a cozy and luxurious stay in a trendy area of the city. Can't wait to come back!

We stayed 4 days here and it was almost perfect. The hotel is located in a quiet and safe residential area at 5 minutes walk from Pyrenees subway station. There are a lot of good bars, restaurants and supermarkets near the place. The room was small, cleaned daily, the bathroom was modern and quite spacious. The first day, there was an awful smell in the bathroom( sewer like) but after we spoke with the guy from the Reception they solved it immediately. The WiFi was great except the last evening. You can have continental breakfast but you have to order it the day before( 14 euros). The lobby and dinning area are very nice and relaxing, they have books, drinks and you can also play backgammon. For smokers it's a special outside place near the Reception. There is a plus that the hotel has an elevator because the stairs are quite narrow. The staff was nice and helpful. If you want to stay in a non touristic area this hotel is a perfect choice.

We stayed at Hotel Scarlett last week; pretty easy to get to via the Métro. It is easier to get to via Pyrénées than Belleville because you walk downhill from Pyrénées. Ask for the building with the elevator or you will have a good leg workout. Bathroom layout is a little weird for two people; it is very narrow but we made it work. Room was very clean and quiet. Staff at Hotel Scarlett are eager to please and very helpful; we stayed in the building without the elevator but the staff brought our bags both up and down. The Belleville area is great for people watching and food; we felt very safe at all hours there; lots of people out on their own late well into the evening; it is always a party on Rue de Belleville at night! Also has bakeries and bookshops. Fantastic blend of old and young locals and newcomers, well-to-do and semi-struggling. Hip eateries and wine bars mix nicely with old established places. Edith Piaf was born around the corner at 72 rue de Belleville; the only bad thing I would say about Belleville is the condition of the front of that building which is a disgrace to both the late, great Piaf and also Paris. The only vineyard in Paris (didn't know that Paris had a vineyard, did you; I didn't either!) is in Parc de Belleville which has an entrance on the next side street going up the hill (vineyard is past the lookout at the top of the park - great view of the skyline of Paris from the lookout). If you want to stay away from the tourists and get a feel for how the residents live, eat and play, come to Belleville and stay at the comfy-cosy Hotel Scarlett!

If you're looking for high-class Paris and tourist locales, this isn't it. But you can get to all those places from the very close metro. What this is, however, is a wonderful location in a working-class neighborhood. The rooms are small. One of the reviewers complained about bathroom next to bed. In fact, it is. Sliding glass door allows light in, but privacy. I did not find an issue. We also had a second room (4 of us) and the bathroom was at end of room, not near bed. It was a larger room (slightly). But we weren't there to hang out in the rooms. We used them to sleep and shower. To that end, these were great rooms. They were clean, modern, the shower was fantastic, the beds comfy. We stayed in a lot of hotels in Europe this summer, and had no complaints about this location.

Now, onto the breakfast. It was a bit pricy, IMO, but worth the cost. The bread was fresh-baked. Fresh cheese, the usual pastries (fresh!), some fruit, yogurt, and a super-automatic espresso machine. (My only complaint is that their cappuccinos added a bit of chocolate. Apparently this is a French thing. I don't like sweet capps, so I made a latte with an extra shot of espresso. Problem solved. Did I mention the bread was fresh-baked?

The best, absolute best, part of the stay was the restaurant 2 doors down, recommended by Hotel Scarlett staff. Le Beratin. You. Must. Go. It was fabulous. Lunch is a better deal, as dinner is all a la carte. I went for both. Brush up on your French. The menu, written daily on a chalk board, is all in French. The gazpacho was amazing! The peaches in (yogurt?) for dessert at lunch was heavenly. I would go back to Paris just to eat there again.

And, lest I forget, the staff at Hotel Scarlett were simply wonderful. They made copies of tickets, gave us directions, suggestions, etc. Would stay there again in a heartbeat.

We loved our stay at Hotel Scarlett. The staff was absolutely exceptional. They were so willing to help us and accommodate us in any way. They made recommendations for restaurants and called about reservations. They printed items for us, brought us wine to the room and made sure our room was cleaned at a time that fit our schedule. The room is small but very well decorated and immaculate. The bed is very comfortable with nice linens. The shower is a good size with plenty of hot water and good water pressure. The lobby is awesome and a great place to hang out. There is a very good optional breakfast in the mornings. The rooms have air conditioning and there is a lift. We loved how they are environmentally conscious. You can leave one of your cards in a slot inside the door and the electricity is turned off while you are away. You pull it out as you enter the room and voila the power is on. Although the main road up to the hotel isn't anything memorable, don't be fooled by this. Just venture down the side roads and you will be pleasantly surprised by the quaintness and the wonderful cafes, restaurants and artists. Everything you could possibly need is 2 minutes away...wine bar, grocery store, butcher shop, bakery and the metro. It is a quick trip to almost anywhere in Paris. This is a great place to stay at a great price. I would 100% recommend it and wouldn't hesitate to stay here again.

I know Paris and sweet little parian style rooms are part of it's character but this was smaller than is nice.The design looks great but the rooms are too tiny for this to be something you enjoy. The double bed had very little room either side and this is where the embarrassment of the bathroom come in. There is a glass sliding door which is not so frosted/ opaque so what ends up happening is you are on the toilet and your partner can hear you and still see you. we tried to laugh about it but we both admitted it was embarrassing. The bathroom left a lot to be desired as the shower also leaked across the floor. The room was so small that there was nowhere to put your suitcase and where it was put didn't get in the way but there really was little space anywhere in the room. The size of the room and with this the cost are two reasons why I would not stay here again.

Our architectural tour group stayed here for four nights. Meticulously restored historic building in the rapidly gentrify-ing Belville precinct near to the Place de la Republique and Pere Lachaise cemetry. Stylish interiors with all the modern cons and pristine bathrooms. Very economical space standards as could be expected in reasonably priced Paris. Excellent bottomless breakfasts of superior quality. Charming young and helpful management. Surroundings teaming with restaurants, chemists, fast food outlets and supermarkets. Four minute walk to the Pyrenees metro and a fifteen minute ride to Chatelet in the heart of Paris. Hope to return someday.

The room was reasonably sized and modern. The location was not in the centre of the city however was walking distance from a metro station. The elevator was an old school one. The only negative was that you could hear other guests walking up and down the stairs from your room. I would try a different hotel next time however enjoyed my stay here.

Great value and fantastic location. We enjoyed our stay and rooms were very comfortable. 4-5 minute walk to Pyrenees/Belleville metro stations which takes 15-20 minutes to get into the heart of Paris. A couple of suggested improvements would be to provide tea making facilities in the bedroom and a mirror in the bedroom (only available in the bathroom. Overall a thoroughly enjoyable stay and Hotel gets our recommendation

That is definitely a good place to stay in Paris.
Nice, clean, and very quiet hotel. It's located close to the subway station Pyrénées and not very far from the Butte Chaumont Parc .
I highly recommend this hotel.

This hotel was a little difficult to find but we arrived very late and the fatigue may have added to the difficulty. The hotel staff was amazing! Very polite and accommodating from helping us with directions, arranging a VERY early ride to the airport for us, and warmly greeting us whenever we saw them. The hotel itself is small but very well designed and is clean. The location is perfect! Lots of little shops and grocery stores near by but it is off the beaten path a bit. I would definitely stay here again!

Spent two nights en route back to the UK after 4 weeks in the south of France. Chose the hotel due to the excellent reviews (thanks) plus it was in an area in Paris I wasn't familiar with. More on the area in a bit.

The hotel was really good. Modern and well appointed, clean and comfortable. The rooms are not large, it is Paris, but "cosy" and a surprisingly spacious shower! The staff were friendly and helpful and clearly enjoyed their role. Had breakfast one morning, plenty of options.

We did stay on a weekend and the street/area was certainly boisterous on Saturday night, the double glazing had to work hard to keep things quiet. The area is certainly interesting, gritty with a heavy Chinese influence. But walk down to the Belleville Boulevard, turn left and it becomes very local very quickly. Metro is handy to the hotel.

Recommended with confidence, great value.

A lovely boutique style hotel with everything needed. Train system had to be learned to get around. Food everywhere was great. Located near ethnic neighborhood (oriental). In between two train stations. McDonalds nearby. Wi-Fi in room. Recommend multiple day transportation pass to get around Paris. Good experience overall.

The Scarlett is a well kept hotel. Bedding was very fresh. The room and bathroom were clean, upscale, and well maintained. The lobby and innerworkings of the hotel are all very clean and atractive. I would honestly say the hotel boarders on being 4 star. The problem is the location. The surrounding neighborhood in the 20th Arr. is safe but run down. It is not the glamerous side of Paris. If you can ignore the neighborhood, then the Scarlett is a great place to stay with reasonable prices.

We stayed for 2 night with our 2 year old baby. The room was very small (with baby bed it was quite uncomfortable). The room was cleaned and bed was comfortable. The bathroom is also very small. The reception desk was very helpful.

Hotel Scarlett is positioned 2 mins from the metro and provides a great location for getting about Paris. The rooms and compact but very well designed providing modern/contemporary decor. Sonia on the desk provided some recommendations for dinner that were fantastic. Highly recommended by me

We stayed here for 3 nights. The staff is young, helpful and kind; it kind of feels like a bunch of folks in hotel management school. Nice little lobby.
Breakfast was very good (although the coffee machine was broke during our visit) - yogurt, fruit, very good bread and pastry, eggs, etc.
The room was nice and clean but very small. My main issue was that there was no place to unpack. No closet or drawers at all. Bathroom small but nice.
The location is indeed close to a subway stop, about a 20 minute ride to major tourist sites. It is a working class neighborhood with no real charm.
From a value standpoint, we ended up paying about $200/night, which is just too much. On our return to Paris, we stayed at a place much closer in, a better neighborhood and paid $130/ night.

Enjoyed several room here and all in our party were very pleased with the hotel rooms (just as pictured on the website) which were contemporary, colorful and exceptionally clean. Beds were comfy. The staff was very helpful and greeted us at the front desk even when we were getting back to the hotel late at night. Excellent location near public transportation. Would definitely stay here again when in Paris.

Very nicely set up rooms, clean and well maintained at all times. Very helpful and polite staff, most accommodating. My husband and I got the breakfast on our last morning, and it was excellent -- a very nice assortment of breads and yogurts and fruit.

One small issue, though. The air conditioning in the rooms is turned off by the cleaning staff, which means that we returned to a very hot and stuffy hotel room after a busy day of tourist activity. Surely some kind of compromise could be reached on this.

A good experience overall! Recommended!

My husband and I stayed here for a couple of nights in May. The hotel is conveniently located near metro stations. The room is cosy, but clean and tidy and nicely decorated. Staff were helpful and pleasant.

Booked a 3 night stay, e-mailed to say I had an unexpected health problem and asked to change dates. Curt, rude and unhelpful reply, (not their problem, its up to the agents, yet they keep my money and no doubt re sell the room) No such thing as service anymore.

This hotel is tucked around the corner in a busy by day and vibrant by night area. We had 2 walking distance accesses to the Metro. We had a very cozy bed that was refreshing after sleeping on a hard bed at the last hotel. There was such a cute window to let us air our clothes after we washed (by hand) and dried easily. The bathroom and shower were great sizes compared to others hotels during our travels. We stayed on the 2nd floor and the stairs were so neat being in a spiral and easy to climb.

We were very pleased with this hotel. The staff was very friendly and helpful. The room was comfortable and everything worked the way it should. The fixtures seemed to be very new. The housekeeping staff did a good job and were very friendly. The AC felt good when we came back from walking in very hot weather. We would definitely use this hotel again.

Quite a way out of the city centre but well located a small hill between two metro stations (so you can walk down hill every time if you like!). You can also get quite a nice distance shot of the Eiffel Tower just a few yards from the hotel. There are plenty of Chinese and Thai restaurants nearby alongside the more traditional places.

Once you step inside, the hotel is beautifully designed and very welcoming. The staff are helpful and welcoming and more than willing to lend you a hotel umbrella, a welcome touch as it was hammering down!

The rooms are pretty small but modern and clean and the beds very comfortable. The bathroom was also very compact but nicely designed with a good shower. However, they need to look at the design here as if the shower is fully on it will flood the floor including heading into the bedroom! Fortunately, we noticed this in time to prevent a serious problem.

Breakfast was absurdly expensive so we didn't bother, but this is Paris so we just grabbed something while we were out.

Overall, a perfectly good choice for those who tend to be out of the hotel all day and a very pleasant return for a good night's sleep. The decor is cool, the staff are excellent but just a few niggles.

The best thing about this hotel was the decor, it was beautifully furnished.
Staff were great and very friendly.
Location was good too, in a less touristy area but close enough to the main attractions.
Rooms were very clean but the standard room was on the small side meaning there was little room for storage and no tea and coffee making facilities.
Would definitely recommend this hotel for your stay in Paris.

Small, compact, modern and affordable hotel. We didn't really eat or drink in the area so would be unfair to rate that. The hotel was clean, modern and the staff were always on hand to assist. Breakfast is a very small affair. At €14 each it is a little expensive for me. I would just on the train, which is 2 mins up the hill or walk down towards the bottom of the hill and eat in a local cafe for the same sort of money. I would say that the only thing missing is a little bar. You could order wine by the bottle I think, but that was it.

I stood in the bathroom with my hands on my hips and my elbows touched the wall on both sides (and I don't have wide hips). A tall person would probably have to sit at an angle on the toilet otherwise their knees would be against the wall. That said, the shower is very powerful and the bathroom is clean and modern. My room was cosy with only a view of the room opposite but well equipped, quiet, clean and with a comfortable bed. The staff are friendly. The lift only seems to serve part of the hotel, as far as I could work out, so it may be worth checking on that if you will have difficulty with stairs. I didn't sample breakfast. It's a boutique hotel with a bit of character, which I prefer to the large chains. Wifi was slow although other reviews don't seem to say the same so perhaps it was my computer or I was unlucky with the room. There are two lovely parks quite nearby. It's not an affluent part of the city but I didn't have any concerns about safety although I saw some drug dealing.

Our room was clean and the fixtures modern. The staff was friendly and went out of their way to be helpful throughout our stay. The free wifi was reliable and consistent. We elected not to pay for breakfast. One should keep in mind that this hotel is not in the very heart of Paris. I did not find this to be an issue as the metro is reliable, but don't think you are going to walk around the Latin Quarter the second you walk outside. You should budget a little extra time to get to wherever you are going. That extra 15 minutes or so was well worth the highly competitive rates. Will certainly consider staying again.

Spent two nights here. Fab hotel. Loved the decor. Room quite small but all we needed. Great shower. Comfy bed.

Didn't have breakfast but loads lovely places around.

Staff friendly. Was hoping for more information regarding good places to go to eat nearby but wandered and found nice Lebanese place across the road for relaxed meal on first night.

Would definitely recommend as think it's a lovely hotel for a good price.

A great 3 days was spent at the Hotel Scarlett. Set in the district of Belleville the hotel is excellent for getting into and out of all the major tourist spots of Paris. Close to two metro stops it took no time at all to get to many attractions. The district looks a little run down but there were plenty of bars and restaurants which were all bustling. The staff were excellent and printed out tickets for attractions no bother. The room was excellent. A good size with excellent air con and bathroom. The only down side was I got in touch with the hotel before our arrival to let them know it was our wedding anniversary and no one got back in touch and there was no acknowledgement of this once we got there.

Upon check-in, the staff were super friendly, knowledgable of the area, and willing to do anything to make my stay as great as possible. The room was small, but laid out in a great way. All of the furniture and amenities in the room seemed very high quality, and the bed was very comfortable with plush, soft linens. The shower in the bathroom is absolutely incredible! I wish my shower at home was that nice. The cleanliness of the room and the hotel in general was perfect. Within walking distance to The Louvre, if you are "a walker", if not, the metro is only 2 minutes away and will take you right there! Great restaurants in the area, a grocery store right around the corner, and one of the best (if not the best) view of Paris 1 block away at the top of a hill, in a beautiful park! Highly recommended hotel!

Very nice rooms. 5 min walk to Pyrenes metro. Cheap food all around. Loved it😆😍. Very convenient to go to city centre or catch a bus. We could see the Eiffel tower from the street. Dont forget to eat street foods. Crepes and a lot of spicy n hot food only 5mins away.
